<!DOCTYPE html>
   <html lang="en">
   <head>
      <meta charset="UTF-8">
      <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

      <!--=============== CSS ===============-->
      <link rel="stylesheet" href="protocols.css">

      <title>Landscape responsive card - Bedimcode</title>
   </head>
   <body>
      <div class="container">
         <div class="card__container">
            <article class="card__article">
               <img src="P-paper.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">

               <div class="card__data">
                  <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                  <h2 class="card__title">Paper</h2>
                  <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling plastic reduces the consumption of raw materials, saves energy, and decreases pollution.
                    Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Improperly disposed plastic can persist in the environment for hundreds of years, causing harm to wildlife through ingestion or entanglement. It also contributes to ocean pollution, harming marine life.</a>
               </div>
            </article>

            <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-plastic.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">Plastic</h2>
                   <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling paper conserves natural resources like trees, reduces energy consumption, and minimizes greenhouse gas emissions.
                     Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Improper disposal of paper can lead to deforestation, habitat destruction, and contamination of soil and waterways.</a>
                </div>
             </article>

             <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-Glass.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">Glass</h2>
                   <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling glass conserves energy, reduces landfill space, and decreases air pollution associated with glass manufacturing.
                    Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Broken glass not properly disposed of can cause injuries to humans and animals. Additionally, glass in landfills takes a long time to decompose and can release harmful chemicals into the environment.</a>
                </div>
             </article>

             <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-metal.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">Metal (e.g., aluminum, steel)</h2>
                   <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling metal saves energy, reduces greenhouse gas emissions, and conserves natural resources.
                    Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Improper disposal of metal can lead to soil and water contamination, and the corrosion of metals in landfills can release toxic substances into the environment.</a>
                </div>
             </article>

             <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-Computer.png" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">Computers (including disks, CPUs, monitors)</h2>
                   <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling computers allows for the recovery of valuable materials such as gold, silver, copper, and aluminum. It reduces the energy and resources required for manufacturing new electronics and prevents hazardous substances from leaching into the environment.
                    Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Improper disposal of computers can lead to the release of toxic substances such as lead, mercury, and brominated flame retardants into the environment, posing risks to human health and ecosystems. Additionally, data security risks arise if personal information stored on hard drives is not properly erased before disposal.</a>
                </div>
             </article>

             <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-phones.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">Mobile Phones</h2>
                   <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling mobile phones conserves precious metals like gold, silver, and palladium, reduces the demand for raw materials, and decreases energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions associated with manufacturing new devices.
                    Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Improper disposal of mobile phones can result in the release of hazardous substances like lead, cadmium, and mercury into the environment. These substances can contaminate soil and water, posing risks to human health and wildlife. Moreover, valuable materials within mobile phones go to waste if not recycled, contributing to resource depletion.</a>
                </div>
             </article>

             <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-battery.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">Batteries (including lithium-ion, nickel-cadmium)</h2>
                   <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling batteries allows for the recovery of valuable metals such as lithium, cobalt, nickel, and cadmium. It reduces the need for raw material extraction, conserves resources, and minimizes environmental pollution.
                    Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Improper disposal of batteries can lead to the release of hazardous chemicals and heavy metals into the environment, contaminating soil, water, and air. This can pose risks to human health and ecosystems, as well as cause fires and explosions in landfills if batteries are damaged or punctured.</a>
                </div>
             </article>

             <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-pcb.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">Printed Circuit Boards (PCBs)</h2>
                   <a>Benefits of Recycling: Recycling PCBs enables the recovery of precious metals like gold, silver, and palladium, as well as valuable metals such as copper and tin. It reduces the environmental impact of mining and processing raw materials and prevents the release of hazardous substances.
                    Hazard if Not Disposed Properly: Improper disposal of PCBs can result in the release of toxic substances like lead, mercury, and brominated flame retardants into the environment, leading to soil and water contamination and posing risks to human health and ecosystems.</a>
                </div>
             </article>

             <article class="card__article">
                <img src="P-food.jpg" alt="image" class="card__img">
 
                <div class="card__data">
                   <!-- <span class="card__description">Vancouver Mountains, Canada</span> -->
                   <h2 class="card__title">leftover food scraps</h2>
                   <a>
                    Step 1: Gather your kitchen scraps. Think fruit and veggie peels, coffee grounds, and eggshells—anything that's not meat or dairy. Chop 'em up into small pieces to speed up the decomposition process.
                    
                    Step 2: Get yourself a compost bin or even a simple container with a lid. Toss those scraps in there, along with some dry materials like shredded paper or leaves to balance out the moisture.
                    
                    Step 3: Mix it up every now and then to help everything break down faster. Think of it as giving your compost a little dance party—turning it keeps the oxygen flowing and helps the microbes do their job.
                    
                    Step 4: Wait for the magic to happen! Over time, those scraps will transform into nutrient-rich fertilizer that your plants will absolutely love. It's like giving them a gourmet meal.
                    
                    Step 5: Spread that black gold in your garden and watch your plants thrive! Your tomatoes will be tastier, your flowers will bloom brighter—it's nature's way of saying 'thanks' for recycling those scraps.</a>
                </div>
             </article>
         </div>
      </div>
   </body>
</html>